05193nam a22008055i 9781845458218DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97818454582187 a10.1515/97818454582182doi  a(DE-B1597)637319  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN476.73b.P6 2012 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a581.6/3422300aPlants, Health and Healing :bOn the Interface of Ethnobotany and Medical Anthropology /ced. by Elisabeth Hsu, Stephen Harris. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEpistemologies of Healing ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tIntroduction. Plants in Medical Practice and Common Sense: On the Interface of Ethnobotany and Medical Anthropol -- tHISTORY -- tEditorial Introduction -- t1. Non-Native Plants and Their Medicinal Uses -- t2. Qing hao (Herba Artemisiae annuae) in the Chinese Materia Medica -- tANTHROPOLOGY -- tEditorial Introduction -- t3. Shamanic Plants and Gender in the Healing Forest -- t4. Persons, Plants and Relations: Treating Childhood Illness in a Western Kenyan Village -- tPLANT PORTRAITS -- tEditorial Introduction -- t5. East goes West. Ginkgo biloba and Dementia -- t6. Medicinal, Stimulant and Ritual Plant Use: an Ethnobotany of Caffeine-Containing Plants -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPlants have cultural histories, as their applications change over time and with place. Some plant species have affected human cultures in profound ways, such as the stimulants tea and coffee from the Old World, or coca and quinine from South America. Even though medicinal plants have always attracted considerable attention, there is surprisingly little research on the interface of ethnobotany and medical anthropology. This volume, which brings together (ethno-)botanists, medical anthropologists and a clinician, makes an important contribution towards filling this gap. It emphasises that plant knowledge arises situationally as an intrinsic part of social relationships, that herbs need to be enticed if not seduced by the healers who work with them, that herbal remedies are cultural artefacts, and that bioprospecting and medicinal plant discovery can be viewed as the epitome of a long history of borrowing, stealing and exchanging plants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBotany, Medical. 0aEthnobotany. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aMedicinal plants. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBlumenshine, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, John Grimley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreedman, Françoise Barbira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeissler, P. Wenzel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHsu, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrince, Ruth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimbul, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeckerle, Caroline S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545821840uhttps://www.degruyte